Do you know the situation of having different application servers running which are very easy to distribute, however being dependent on that one huge database server in the back, which has to handle all the queries alone? On the one side it is very easy to scale up the CPU and reputation power, but on the other side what happens if the server is down? Or even if the server is too small for the needed requirements? With installing CRATE you can easily build a way around the problem by simply installing the elastic data store on every application server.

If you want to listen to Bernd and see how he managed to get rid of his old database server by building Crate you should <a title="no more database servers" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVlcmEzb_18&amp;list=UUcp_IqjXaejmwBcwg51n1AA" target="_blank">watch the movie</a>. Find even more relevant information about CrateIO here: <a href="https://crate.io/docs/" target="_blank">https://crate.io/docs/</a>.

<a class="button" href="/download/">Download</a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Nowadays a lot of database solutions provide an easy start with a single node setup. However when your data grow and you have to think about how to scale the backend, things can become very difficult. CrateIO provides a database solution that is as easy to maintain with one node as with multiple nodes and also you can keep the administration overhead as little as possible. Do you want to know how to use Crate in a mutlinode setup? Please <a href="https://crate.io/blog/using-crate-in-multinode-setup/">find the information here</a>.

Listen to Sebastian <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OBlr2D9UCqo">talking about the benefits of a shared nothing architecture</a> and get to know Crate.

